# meta-tegra-xen: Software Defined Vehicle (SDV) Platform Layer

This layer provides a production-ready Yocto environment for configuring Software Defined Vehicle (SDV) architectures on NVIDIA Jetson hardware. By leveraging the Xen hypervisor, this layer enables secure workload consolidation, robust isolation, and high-performance hardware virtualization tailored for modern automotive edge computing and autonomous driving applications.

## Architecture & Project Status

Modern SDV architectures require isolating mixed-criticality systems (e.g., Infotainment, ADAS, Telematics) on a single physical System-on-Chip (SoC). This layer configures a Xen-based virtualization environment tailored for these advanced use cases:

*   **dom0 (Control Domain)**: Privileged control domain managing hardware resources and orchestration.
*   **domD (Driver Domain) - [OPERATIONAL]**: Fully functional driver domain with direct GPU passthrough. This allows near-native graphical and CUDA API performance for hardware-accelerated workloads (e.g., AI/ML inference, ADAS).
*   **domUs (Unprivileged Domains) - [WIP]**: Isolated, general-purpose compute domains for unprivileged applications (currently Work In Progress).

## Dependencies

This layer relies on the standard Yocto Project build system and the following meta-layers:

  URI: https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra.git
  branch: master (or matching release branch)

  URI: git://git.yoctoproject.org/meta-virtualization
  branch: master (or matching release branch)

## Adding the meta-tegra-xen layer to your build

To integrate this layer into your SDV Yocto Project build environment, execute:

```bash
bitbake-layers add-layer meta-tegra-xen
```

*Note: To enable and build the Driver Domain (`domD`) mentioned above, you must also add the `meta-xt-orin-domD` layer to your build:*

```bash
bitbake-layers add-layer meta-xt-orin-domD
```

## Quick Start
Once the layers are configured and dependencies are met, build the SDV reference virtualization image:

```bash
bitbake tegra-xen-image
```

